!! LLM documentation (progressive disclosure)

Plugins can ship documentation tiddlers specifically designed for LLM consumption via the llm-connect tool system. These enable the LLM to learn about plugin mechanics on demand rather than through a bloated system prompt.

!!! Namespace convention

LLM doc tiddlers must live ''outside'' the protected `$:/plugins/rimir/` prefix so they are accessible through llm-connect's restricted wiki proxy. The convention is:

```
$:/rimir/llm-doc/<pluginName>/<topic>
```

Examples:
* `$:/rimir/llm-doc/appify/overview`
* `$:/rimir/llm-doc/appify/channels`
* `$:/rimir/llm-doc/runner/actions`

The tiddlers still ship as shadow tiddlers inside the plugin (files in `llm-doc/` directory). The `title:` field in each `.tid` file overrides the path-derived title.

!!! Why `$:/rimir/llm-doc/`?

LLM doc tiddlers use the `$:/rimir/llm-doc/` namespace rather than living under `$:/plugins/rimir/`. This keeps them separate from plugin internals and makes them easy to discover via tag filters. The llm-connect deny filter does not block `$:/plugins/rimir/` by default, but users or specific chats may choose to exclude plugin namespaces via the excluded-plugins setting — the `$:/rimir/llm-doc/` namespace is unaffected by those exclusions.

Runtime configs that the LLM might need to read/write should be in `$:/config/rimir/` (standard TW convention), not inside the plugin.

!!! Structure

Each doc tiddler is tagged `$:/tags/rimir/<pluginName>/llm-doc` for plugin-specific discovery. The plugin provides a guide tool that lists available docs with descriptions.

|!Field |!Description |
|`tags` |`$:/tags/rimir/<pluginName>/llm-doc` |
|`description` |One-line summary — the LLM reads this to decide relevance |
|`llm-sort` |Sort order (numeric string, e.g., `01`, `02`) |

!!! Progressive disclosure pattern

Docs form a browsable tree:

# The LLM calls a guide tool → gets a table of contents (title + description per doc)
# The LLM picks a relevant doc → calls `get_tiddler` to read it
# The doc may reference deeper docs → the LLM follows the trail as needed
# The LLM stops drilling when it has enough context to act

This keeps token usage minimal — the LLM only reads what it needs for the current task.

!!! Plugin shadow tiddlers and LLM access

Plugin shadow tiddlers under `$:/plugins/rimir/` are accessible to the LLM by default (the deny filter only blocks `[tag[sensitive]]`). Users can restrict access to specific plugin namespaces via the excluded-plugins checkbox in llm-connect settings, or by extending the deny filter.

The appify clone widgets strip `$:/tags/rimir/llm-accessible` from cloned tiddlers — this tag is a legacy marker from when the deny filter blocked all rimir plugin shadows. It has no effect on the current protection filter but is still cleaned up during cloning to avoid stale tags on user tiddlers.

!!! Wikitext in doc tiddlers

Doc tiddlers can contain wikitext that renders context-specific information (e.g., a `$list` showing the current app's channels). The LLM can use `wikitext_render` on such content to get live, contextual output. This bridges static documentation with dynamic state.

